When you walk in to @cresseysportsperformance-FL, this is the first jersey you’ll see - and it's by design, as nobody could embody everything CSP is about more than Steve Cishek (@srshrek31). After 13 CSP offseasons and 11+ years of MLB service time, he announced his retirement, ending an amazing career both on and off the field. He started out as a diehard minor leaguer who would drive 4hrs 4x/week to train at our MA facility, and 8 years later, became a crucial factor in us opening CSP-FL, as he'd relocated to FL. We couldn't imagine a better ambassador around whom to build our business.
 
You won't meet anyone who has a bad thing to say about Steve, and we've gotten countless referrals from our relationship with him. I once asked him why he has so many raving fans, and Steve responded that wherever he goes, he just tries to serve those around him, whether in a clubhouse or a community. Without ever asking for recognition, he's gone out of his way to mentor (and even financially support) minor leaguers, amateur players, and others in the community. Character is who you are when nobody is watching - and while Steve performed in front of large crowds, his greatest successes will always be the private accolades he deserved, but never sought out.
 
Personally, the Cresseys owe a ton to Steve and his wonderful wife, @mcishek, who also happen to be our neighbors. Our combined 6 (!) daughters are attached at the hip, and learned to ride bikes and swim together as our families spent every day together during the early months of the pandemic. I've lost track of how many Christmas Day meetups and family dinners we've shared. Professionally, Steve taught me far more than I could’ve ever taught him, and I'm a better coach, listener, and communicator because of him. He always put in the work - and it's this work that allowed him to go a full career without a single day on the disabled list with an arm injury in spite of a funky delivery.
 
Thank you, congratulations, and happy retirement, buddy. You left the game much better than you found it. @annacressey will make chicken thighs to celebrate. #CSPFamily for life; just let us know when you're ready for that sidearm camp.

Posted @withregram • @ericcressey Serratus anterior gets a lot of love as a scapular protractor, some love as a scapular upward rotator, even less love as a posterior tilter of the scapula, and just about zero love for its impact on rib internal/external rotation.

Most importantly, you'll see that the upper fibers of the serratus anterior attach on the first rib - the very bone that's removed during thoracic outlet surgery. When the serratus fires, it depresses the first rib and clears space under the clavicle for important nerve and vascular structures to pass. If you swipe left, you'll appreciate that this attachment effectively makes serratus anterior an antagonist to the scalenes and subclavius, which both elevate the first rib. 

This is one reason why a lot of the thoracic outlet syndrome cases you'll encounter aren't your classic kyphotic (hunchback) posture, but actually a lot of flat thoracic spine, heavy scapular downward rotation/depression, and horizontal clavicle presentations. Getting serratus anterior going favorably impacts scapular upward rotation (which brings the clavicle up), first rib positioning, and the ideal convex-concave relationship between the rib cage and scapula.

Fun facts: it also indirectly impacts contralateral thoracic rotation, but that's a post for another day.

Here’s a quick look at an athlete with limited active hip extension. On the first rep, I just asked him to extend his hip. On the second rep, I encouraged him to do whatever he could to get more ROM - simulating what would happen in a longer stride while sprinting, or in his case, getting down the mound as a right handed pitcher. You’ll see that he compensates by extending through the lumbar spine. Not surprisingly, he had a history of low back irritation with distance running, various weight training exercises, and pitching.

Other potential compensations could be increased abduction/external rotation of the hip, or an increase in anterior glide of the head of the femur (harder to spot). Basically, athletes will do whatever they can to compensate - and that can lead to both inefficient movement and pain.

The lesson? Adequate hip extension is a must for optimal function. Screen for it both passively AND actively. #cspfamily

Awesome heads-up hustle play by @isiahkf here - and also an important lesson on the baseball preparation side of things. IKF's peak speed on this was 25.8 ft/s, which is a few ticks off his Statcast 2023 average of 27.7 ft/s. Per Baseball Savant:

'For a player’s seasonal average, the following two types of plays currently qualify for inclusion in Sprint Speed. The best of these runs, approximately two-thirds, are averaged for a player’s seasonal average.
* Runs of two bases or more on non-homers, excluding being a runner on second base when an extra base hit happens
* Home to first on “topped” or “weakly hit” balls.'

Even with a walking/up-tempo start (as opposed to a standstill), he was in acceleration mode the entire time. On a baseball field, you aren't going to sniff top speed in upright sprinting very often - so a lot of big plays that decide games are going to hinge on how well athletes accelerate.

Your training needs to reflect that. The overwhelming majority of your sprint work shouldn't be upright over longer distances. It should be focused on getting moving quickly.

A perk of training acceleration hard is that it's rarely how athletes get hurt with sprinting. You can safely do a lot of reps at short distances. Sprinting with sleds and against bands or chains are ways to not only change the stimulus, but even reinforce proper acceleration mechanics. Here is my hand (at 5-8) compared to the hand of a pitcher who is 6-8. Meanwhile, the baseball is the same size for both of us.

To manipulate the baseball, he has to close his hands more. Meanwhile, me holding a baseball keeps me a bit closer to the anatomical position.

Now, consider that many of the muscles that work to close the hands (flexors) actually attach on the medial epicondyle via the common flexor tendon. Therefore, a lot of extra tone further up the chain can come from longer term density changes at the hand. We usually talk about working proximal to distal, but in this case, the distal (hand) can impact the proximal (elbow)  heavily.

Doing more targeted manual therapy, range of motion, and strength work at the wrist/hand has been a big difference maker for us. And, in many cases, it helps to make more of your proximal changes "stick" a bit better. 

Try digging in on the soft tissue structures of the hand in throwers; you might be surprised at what you find. #cspfamily

𝟭𝟭 𝗪𝗮𝘆𝘀 𝗧𝗼 𝗣𝗿𝗼𝗴𝗿𝗲𝘀𝘀 𝗜𝗻𝘃𝗲𝗿𝘁𝗲𝗱 𝗥𝗼𝘄𝘀⬇️

1️⃣ Do them correctly! 
Make a straight line from your heels to your head. The most common errors we see in most folks’ technique are: forward head posture, elbows drifting behind the body (scapula doesn’t retract, so the lifter substitutes extra movement of the humerus), and hip sagging. 

2️⃣ Change the grip. 
Just as we see with pull-up variations, going to a pronated (overhand) grip will increase the difficulty of inverted rows, as compared to neutral (palms facing one another) and supinated (underhand) grips.

3️⃣ Try some mechanical advantage drop sets.
If you’re someone who can bang out inverted reps pretty easily and want a crazy challenge, try doing the first half of your set pronated, and then switching to supinated for the second half when you fatigue. 

4️⃣ Add isometric holds at the top. 
The top position is without a doubt the most challenging, so you can increase the time under tension - and therefore the difficulty - by adding 1-3 second pauses at the top of each rep.

5️⃣ Lengthen the eccentric portion.
In addition to holding an isometric at the top of each rep, another great way to progress this movement is to lengthen the amount of time descending from the top to the bottom of each rep. 

6️⃣ Elevate the feet.
This progression is somewhat “assumed,” but most people overlook the fact that you can elevate the feet a lot further than you might think. We like to use the 24” box.

7️⃣ Load with chains
8️⃣Wear a weight vest.
9️⃣ Load with a backpack. 
The extra padding made it conducive to adding extra loading, as you can slide plates up to 25 pounds (the diameter on anything heavier is too much to fit).  Just strap it on your chest and wear it in reverse for your inverted rows. 
🔟Use Fat Gripz.
Adding load and range of motion aren’t the only way to increase the difficulty of inverted rows; you can also challenge the grip more aggressively.
1️⃣1️⃣ Go to one-arm variations.
You can do inverted row variations one arm at a time, too.  In doing so, you add a little more of a challenge to rotary stability of the core.
